Chapter 11 Measuring Performance in Classification Models

This is an implementation of the material in Chapter 11 of Applied Predictive Modeling by Max Kuhn and Kjell Johnson[^1]. In this notebook I have reproduced some of the analysis and plots from the chapter. The authors used the lattice package for plotting, but I have reproduced the plots using ggplot2.

Setup:

11.1 Class Predictions

A simple softmax transformation function to recreate the calculations on page 248:

softmax_trans <- function(y) {
  p <- exp(y)/sum(exp(y))
  return(p)
}

softmax_trans(c(0.25, 0.76, -0.1)) %>% round(2)
[1] 0.30 0.49 0.21

Well-Calibrated Probabilities

Generate the data required for the analysis and plots in this section:

# Simulate some two class data with two predictors
set.seed(975)
training <- quadBoundaryFunc(500)
testing <- quadBoundaryFunc(1000)
testing$class2 <- ifelse(testing$class == "Class1", 1, 0)
testing$ID <- 1:nrow(testing)

# Fit models
qdaFit <- qda(class ~ X1 + X2, data = training)
rfFit <- randomForest(class ~ X1 + X2, data = training, ntree = 2000)

# Predict the test set
testing$qda <- predict(qdaFit, testing)$posterior[,1]
testing$rf <- predict(rfFit, testing, type = "prob")[,1]

# Generate the calibration analysis
calData1 <- calibration(class ~ qda + rf, data = testing, cuts = 10)

Fig. 11.2:

Generate the recalibrated versions:

# To calibrate the data, treat the probabilities as inputs into the model:
trainProbs <- training
trainProbs$qda <- predict(qdaFit)$posterior[,1]

# These models take the probabilities as inputs and, based on the
# true class, re-calibrate them.
nbCal <- NaiveBayes(class ~ qda, data = trainProbs, usekernel = TRUE)

# We use relevel() here because glm() models the probability of the second factor level:
lrCal <- glm(relevel(class, "Class2") ~ qda, data = trainProbs, family = binomial)

# Now re-predict the test set using the modified class probability estimates:
testing$qda2 <- predict(nbCal, testing[, "qda", drop = FALSE])$posterior[,1]
testing$qda3 <- predict(lrCal, testing[, "qda", drop = FALSE], type = "response")


# Manipulate the data a bit for pretty plotting
simulatedProbs <- testing[, c("class", "rf", "qda3")]
names(simulatedProbs) <- c("TrueClass", "RandomForestProb", "QDACalibrated")
simulatedProbs$RandomForestClass <-  predict(rfFit, testing)

calData2 <- calibration(class ~ qda + qda2 + qda3, data = testing)
calData2$data$calibModelVar <- as.character(calData2$data$calibModelVar)
calData2$data$calibModelVar <- ifelse(calData2$data$calibModelVar == "qda", 
                                      "QDA",
                                      calData2$data$calibModelVar)
calData2$data$calibModelVar <- ifelse(calData2$data$calibModelVar == "qda2", 
                                      "Bayesian Calibration",
                                      calData2$data$calibModelVar)

calData2$data$calibModelVar <- ifelse(calData2$data$calibModelVar == "qda3", 
                                      "Sigmoidal Calibration",
                                      calData2$data$calibModelVar)

calData2$data$calibModelVar <- factor(calData2$data$calibModelVar,
                                      levels = c("QDA", 
                                                 "Bayesian Calibration", 
                                                 "Sigmoidal Calibration"))

Presenting Class Probabilities

Generate the model using the German credit data:

# Recreate the model used in the over-fitting chapter
data(GermanCredit)

# First, remove near-zero variance predictors then get rid of a few predictors 
# that duplicate values. For example, there are two possible values for the 
# housing variable: "Rent", "Own" and "ForFree". So that we don't have linear
# dependencies, we get rid of one of the levels (e.g. "ForFree")

GermanCredit <- GermanCredit[, -nearZeroVar(GermanCredit)]
GermanCredit$CheckingAccountStatus.lt.0 <- NULL
GermanCredit$SavingsAccountBonds.lt.100 <- NULL
GermanCredit$EmploymentDuration.lt.1 <- NULL
GermanCredit$EmploymentDuration.Unemployed <- NULL
GermanCredit$Personal.Male.Married.Widowed <- NULL
GermanCredit$Property.Unknown <- NULL
GermanCredit$Housing.ForFree <- NULL

# Split the data into training (80%) and test sets (20%):
set.seed(100)
inTrain <- createDataPartition(GermanCredit$credit_risk, p = .8)[[1]] # changed `$class` to `$credit_risk`
GermanCreditTrain <- GermanCredit[ inTrain, ]
GermanCreditTest  <- GermanCredit[-inTrain, ]

set.seed(1056)
logisticReg <- train(credit_risk ~ ., # changed `class` to `credit_risk`
                     data = GermanCreditTrain,
                     method = "glm",
                     trControl = trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", 
                                              repeats = 5))

The above table and metrics are calculated using the function caret::confusionMatrix(). Once the confusion matrix is obtained, all of these metrics can be calculated manually. The below code is a rough guide to manually calculating each value:

# Obtain the actual confusion matrix:
tbl <- confusion_mat$table

# Accuracy:
(tbl %>% diag(.) %>% sum()) / sum(tbl)
[1] 0.715
# No Information Rate (number of `good`s divide by total):
sum(tbl[, 1])/sum(tbl)
[1] 0.7
# P-value:
# The p-value is calculated using a binomial test (I got this code from the source code for caret: https://github.com/topepo/caret/blob/master/pkg/caret/R/confusionMatrix.R)
test1 <- binom.test(sum(diag(tbl)),
                    sum(tbl),
                    p = max(apply(tbl, 2, sum)/sum(tbl)),
                    alternative = "greater")
test1$p.value
[1] 0.3532
# The confidence interval produced by the above test is not the same as the output from confusionMatrix().
# Instead this is calculated using the below code (taken from the source code).
# The difference is that the hypothesis test uses p = 0.7 in the call to binom.test() whereas the CI uses the default p = 0.5:
binom.test(sum(diag(tbl)), sum(tbl))$conf.int[c(1, 2)]
[1] 0.6471 0.7764
# Mcnemar's Test p-value:
mcnemar.test(x = creditResults$pred, y = creditResults$obs)$p.value %>% round(4)
[1] 0.0341

The rest of the values (Sensitivity, Specificity) can be calculated using the formulas in the help page for confusionMatrix():

A <- tbl[1, 1]
B <- tbl[1, 2]
C <- tbl[2, 1]
D <- tbl[2, 2]
beta <- 1 # for calculating F1 below

sensitivity  <-  A/(A+C)
specificity <- D/(B+D)
prevalence <- (A+C)/(A+B+C+D)
PPV <- (sensitivity * prevalence)/((sensitivity*prevalence) + ((1-specificity)*(1-prevalence)))
NPV <- (specificity * (1-prevalence))/(((1-sensitivity)*prevalence) + ((specificity)*(1-prevalence)))
Detection_Rate <- A/(A+B+C+D)
Detection_Prevalence <- (A+B)/(A+B+C+D)
Balanced_Accuracy <- (sensitivity+specificity)/2
precision <- A/(A+B)
recall <- A/(A+C)
F1 <- (1+beta^2)*precision*recall/((beta^2 * precision)+recall)

metrics_list <- c(sensitivity, specificity, prevalence, PPV, NPV, Detection_Rate, Detection_Prevalence, Balanced_Accuracy, precision, recall , F1)

Compare the two methods to show they are in agreement:

Manually calculate kappa using the source code from the e1071::classAgreement() function (see https://github.com/cran/e1071/blob/master/R/matchClasses.R for source code):

n <- sum(tbl)
ni <- apply(tbl, 1, sum)
nj <- apply(tbl, 2, sum)
lev <- intersect (colnames (tbl), rownames(tbl))
p0 <- sum(diag(tbl[lev, lev]))/n # O
pc <- sum(ni[lev] * nj[lev])/n^2 # E
kappa = (p0 - pc)/(1 - pc) # (O - E)/(1 - E)
kappa
[1] 0.2617

Fig 11.5 (top panel)

prevalence_curve <- expand_grid(
  prevalence = seq(0, 1, len = 100),
  sensitivity = c(0.9, 0.99),
  specificity = 0.95
) %>% 
  mutate(PPV = (sensitivity * prevalence)/((sensitivity * prevalence) + ((1 - specificity) * (1 - prevalence))),
         NPV = (specificity * (1 - prevalence))/((prevalence * (1 - sensitivity)) + (specificity * (1 - prevalence))),
         sensitivity = factor(sensitivity))
ggplot(prevalence_curve) +
  geom_line(aes(prevalence, PPV, group = sensitivity, color = sensitivity)) +
  geom_line(data = filter(prevalence_curve, sensitivity == 0.9),
            aes(prevalence, NPV),
            color = "black", linetype = "dotted") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.2)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 1, by = 0.2)) +
  labs(x = "Prevalence", y = NULL, title = "Fig. 11.5 (Top panel)") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

11.3 Evaluating Class Probabilities

Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curves

The yardstick package can be used to generate data for an ROC curve. The plot can easily be made using autoplot():

yardstick::roc_curve(data = creditResults, obs, prob, event_level = "second") %>% 
  autoplot()

Lift Charts

The yardstick package can be used to generate data for a lift chart (referred to as a gain curve). The plot can easily be made using autoplot():

yardstick::gain_curve(data = creditResults, obs, prob, event_level = "second") %>%
